--- combination(n) { |c| block }    -> Array
--- combination(n)                  -> Enumerable::Enumerator

When invoked with a block, yields all combinations of length
n of elements from ary and then returns ary itself. The implementation
makes no guarantees about the order in which the combinations
are yielded.

When invoked without a block, returns an enumerator object instead.

Examples:

    a = [1, 2, 3, 4]
    a.combination(1).to_a  #=> [[1],[2],[3],[4]]
    a.combination(2).to_a  #=> [[1,2],[1,3],[1,4],[2,3],[2,4],[3,4]]
    a.combination(3).to_a  #=> [[1,2,3],[1,2,4],[1,3,4],[2,3,4]]
    a.combination(4).to_a  #=> [[1,2,3,4]]
    a.combination(0).to_a  #=> [[]]: one combination of length 0
    a.combination(5).to_a  #=> []  : no combinations of length 5

